From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: gregordinary <33880035+gregordinary@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Tue, 30 Jun 2026 12:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] rocket: program the NPU compute clock from runtime-resume
 (clock lever)

Add the rocket_npu_clk_hz module param: when set, (re)program the shared SCMI
NPU compute clock ("npu") from runtime-resume -- only after the PM core has
powered the domain, since setting it cold wedges SCMI -- and park it back at the
vendor 200 MHz POWER_DOWN rate on suspend. 0 leaves the DT default (200 MHz).
On the RK3588 this takes the NPU from its 200 MHz stock rate to a validated
600 MHz.

The park is REFCOUNTED, because the compute clock is ONE SCMI clock shared by
every core ("npu", id 6: clk_summary shows a single scmi_clk_npu rate with
fdab/fdac/fdad0000.npu all as consumers) while runtime-PM is PER core. Parking
it from a per-core suspend callback drops the shared rate to 200 MHz out from
under the cores that are still running -- and it sticks, because a core that is
still runtime-ACTIVE never re-raises it: pm_runtime_get on an already-active
device fires no resume callback. So the rate does not dip, it stays down until
that core happens to suspend and resume. Measured on a Turing RK1 without the
refcount: a resident-int8 matmul across 3 worker fds at the stock 50 ms
autosuspend alternated 15 ms / 69 ms run to run, indefinitely -- a 4.8x swing,
with scmi_clk_npu flapping 200 <-> 600 MHz. Work is fanned across per-fd worker
queues by default in this stack, so any multi-core NPU workload is exposed.

Hence rocket_clk_users: only the LAST core down parks the clock. It counts cores
that are runtime-resumed independently of rocket_npu_clk_hz, so that flipping
that (sysfs-writable) param while cores are active cannot strand the count, and
the decrement sits after the rocket_job_is_idle() -EBUSY bail, so a core that
refuses to suspend still holds the rate. A mutex rather than a bare atomic: it
must serialise the clk_set_rate against a concurrent resume on another core, and
both callbacks run in process context and may sleep.

The park also needs a DEADLINE that outlives a host-side gap WITHIN one
inference, so rocket_autosuspend_ms (default 1000 ms) replaces the hardcoded
50 ms. Upstream's 50 ms is stated as "~3 frames at 60Hz" -- sized for a media
pipeline that submits one inference per frame, where the only idle gaps that
matter fall BETWEEN inferences. An LLM/ASR workload breaks that assumption: the
host packs the operands into the NPU's native tiled layout (the NPU cannot tile
row-major data on-chip, so the scatter is irreducible host work), and a SINGLE
inference therefore contains host gaps in which every core goes idle. At 50 ms
those gaps trip runtime suspend mid-inference: the last core down parks the
shared clock, and the next submit runs at 200 MHz until it ramps back. The clock
lever then silently undoes itself on exactly the workloads it exists for. The
SCMI clock sampled through ONE whisper base.en encode at the stock 50 ms:

    200 200 200 200 200 600 600 600 200 600 600 600 600 600   (MHz)

and that encode is SLOWER than the CPU running the same work. Encode time on a
Turing RK1 at 600 MHz, 4 reps (CPU reference 1628-1639 ms):

    autosuspend    encode (ms)
      50           1881 / 1734 / 1884 / 1809     <- variable, slower than CPU
     100           1275 / 1383 / 1279 / 1286
     200           1275 / 1272 / 1262 / 1265
     500           1259 / 1254 / 1263 / 1269
    1000           1267 / 1253 / 1254 / 1263
    2000           1273 / 1270 / 1264 / 1256

It saturates by ~200 ms; 1000 ms is that knee plus headroom for a large encoder,
whose packing gaps are several times longer (they scale with the weight bytes).
Park-at-idle is preserved -- only its deadline moves -- and 0 restores the PM
core's own default. Kept in this patch rather than a separate one because the
park is introduced HERE: stock mainline never re-rates the clock, so without the
lever there is nothing to park and nothing to fix.

A clk_set_rate failure on resume propagates: undo the bulk-clock enable and
return the error rather than silently returning 0 with the device half-
programmed, so the PM core leaves the domain suspended instead of running it at
an unintended rate.

The "npu" clock handle is acquired ONCE via devm_clk_get_optional() in
rocket_core_init and stashed in struct rocket_core, rather than a clk_get/clk_put
on every resume/suspend (a hot path). -EPROBE_DEFER is propagated; an absent
clock degrades to the stock 200 MHz and never fails probe.

This does not make rates above 600 MHz safe: staggered multi-core resume already
powers a domain on at a rate a sibling raised, so that exposure is pre-existing,
and a pinned 900 MHz hard-locks the box. 600 MHz is the only validated operating
point.
---
 drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.c |  54 ++++++++++++++--
 drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.h |  10 +++
 drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_drv.c  | 111 +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 3 files changed, 170 insertions(+), 5 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.c b/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.c
index b3b2fa9..ebde9dd 100644
--- a/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.c
+++ b/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.c
@@ -7,6 +7,7 @@
 #include <linux/dma-mapping.h>
 #include <linux/err.h>
 #include <linux/iommu.h>
+#include <linux/moduleparam.h>
 #include <linux/platform_device.h>
 #include <linux/pm_runtime.h>
 #include <linux/reset.h>
@@ -14,6 +15,17 @@
 #include "rocket_core.h"
 #include "rocket_job.h"
 
+/*
+ * Deadline for the clock park below (see rocket_device_runtime_suspend() in
+ * rocket_drv.c). The stock 50 ms is too eager once the park exists: it fires
+ * INSIDE a single inference, not just between inferences. 0 leaves the PM core's
+ * own default untouched.
+ */
+static unsigned int rocket_autosuspend_ms = 1000;
+module_param(rocket_autosuspend_ms, uint, 0644);
+MODULE_PARM_DESC(rocket_autosuspend_ms,
+	"runtime-PM autosuspend delay in ms (default 1000; 0 = leave the PM core default)");
+
 int rocket_core_init(struct rocket_core *core)
 {
 	struct device *dev = core->dev;
@@ -32,6 +44,25 @@ int rocket_core_init(struct rocket_core *core)
 	if (err)
 		return dev_err_probe(dev, err, "failed to get clocks for core %d\n", core->index);
 
+	/*
+	 * Acquire the shared SCMI NPU compute clock ("npu") once, for the device
+	 * lifetime, so the rocket_npu_clk_hz re-rate in runtime-resume/suspend
+	 * needs no per-transition clk_get/clk_put (mirrors the npu_supply
+	 * regulator acquisition). It is only RE-RATED from runtime-resume, never
+	 * set cold (that wedges SCMI). Optional: a board without the clock just
+	 * runs stock 200 MHz and never fails to probe -- the "degrade, don't
+	 * disrupt" rule of the clock lever. -EPROBE_DEFER is propagated so the
+	 * clock is retried once its provider is up.
+	 */
+	core->npu_clk = devm_clk_get_optional(dev, "npu");
+	if (IS_ERR(core->npu_clk)) {
+		if (PTR_ERR(core->npu_clk) == -EPROBE_DEFER)
+			return PTR_ERR(core->npu_clk);
+		dev_info(dev, "rocket: no \"npu\" clock (%ld); NPU clock scaling disabled\n",
+			 PTR_ERR(core->npu_clk));
+		core->npu_clk = NULL;
+	}
+
 	core->pc_iomem = devm_platform_ioremap_resource_byname(pdev, "pc");
 	if (IS_ERR(core->pc_iomem)) {
 		dev_err(dev, "couldn't find PC registers %ld\n", PTR_ERR(core->pc_iomem));
@@ -68,12 +99,25 @@ int rocket_core_init(struct rocket_core *core)
 	pm_runtime_use_autosuspend(dev);
 
 	/*
-	 * As this NPU will be most often used as part of a media pipeline that
-	 * ends presenting in a display, choose 50 ms (~3 frames at 60Hz) as an
-	 * autosuspend delay as that will keep the device powered up while the
-	 * pipeline is running.
+	 * The park above needs a deadline that outlives a host-side gap WITHIN one
+	 * inference, not merely the gap between inferences.
+	 *
+	 * Upstream's 50 ms is "~3 frames at 60Hz" -- sized for a media pipeline that
+	 * submits one inference per frame, where the only idle gaps that matter fall
+	 * BETWEEN inferences. An LLM/ASR workload breaks that assumption: the host
+	 * packs the operands into the NPU's native tiled layout (it cannot be done
+	 * on-chip), so a SINGLE inference contains host-side gaps in which every core
+	 * goes idle. At 50 ms those gaps trip runtime suspend mid-inference, the last
+	 * core down parks the shared clock to 200 MHz, and the next submit runs at a
+	 * third of the rate until it ramps back -- so the clock lever silently undoes
+	 * itself on exactly the workloads it exists for.
+	 *
+	 * 1000 ms is past the measured knee (~200 ms on a small encoder) with headroom
+	 * for a large one, whose packing gaps are several times longer (they scale with
+	 * the weight bytes). Park-at-idle is preserved; only its deadline moves.
 	 */
-	pm_runtime_set_autosuspend_delay(dev, 50);
+	if (rocket_autosuspend_ms)
+		pm_runtime_set_autosuspend_delay(dev, rocket_autosuspend_ms);
 
 	pm_runtime_enable(dev);
 
diff --git a/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.h b/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.h
index f6d7382..1080f3b 100644
--- a/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.h
+++ b/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_core.h
@@ -39,6 +39,16 @@ struct rocket_core {
 	struct clk_bulk_data clks[4];
 	struct reset_control_bulk_data resets[2];
 
+	/*
+	 * Shared SCMI NPU compute clock ("npu"), acquired once for the device
+	 * lifetime (devm) so runtime-resume/suspend can re-rate it without a
+	 * clk_get/clk_put on every PM transition. NULL when no "npu" clock is
+	 * wired (then the rocket_npu_clk_hz lever is a no-op). Only ever re-rated
+	 * from runtime-resume/suspend, never set cold (that wedges SCMI). See
+	 * rocket_drv.c.
+	 */
+	struct clk *npu_clk;
+
 	struct iommu_group *iommu_group;
 
 	struct mutex job_lock;
diff --git a/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_drv.c b/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_drv.c
index 8bbbce5..3dd6536 100644
--- a/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_drv.c
+++ b/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_drv.c
@@ -9,6 +9,7 @@
 #include <linux/clk.h>
 #include <linux/err.h>
 #include <linux/iommu.h>
+#include <linux/mutex.h>
 #include <linux/of.h>
 #include <linux/platform_device.h>
 #include <linux/pm_runtime.h>
@@ -25,6 +26,39 @@
 static struct platform_device *drm_dev;
 static struct rocket_device *rdev;
 
+#define ROCKET_NPU_POWER_DOWN_HZ	200000000UL	/* vendor POWER_DOWN_FREQ */
+
+/*
+ * The compute clock is ONE SCMI clock shared by every core, but runtime-PM is
+ * PER core -- so the park must be refcounted, or one core going idle drops the
+ * rate out from under the cores that are still running.
+ *
+ * The damage is not merely a mid-flight rate cut: a core that is still
+ * runtime-ACTIVE never re-raises the clock (pm_runtime_get on an active device
+ * fires no resume callback), so once a sibling parks the rate that core keeps
+ * running at 200 MHz until it happens to suspend and resume. Only the LAST core
+ * down may park the clock.
+ *
+ * Counts cores that are runtime-resumed, independent of rocket_npu_clk_hz, so
+ * that flipping the (sysfs-writable) param while cores are active cannot strand
+ * the count. Serialised against a concurrent resume on another core -- both
+ * callbacks run in process context and may sleep, so this is a mutex, not an
+ * atomic: it guards the rate change as well as the count.
+ */
+static DEFINE_MUTEX(rocket_clk_lock);
+static unsigned int rocket_clk_users;
+
+/*
+ * If non-zero, program the shared SCMI NPU compute clock ("npu") to this rate
+ * from runtime-resume, i.e. only AFTER the PM core has powered the domain.
+ * 0 leaves the DT default (200 MHz) untouched (stock). Writable via sysfs so
+ * the rate can be swept without rebuilding.
+ */
+static unsigned long rocket_npu_clk_hz;
+module_param(rocket_npu_clk_hz, ulong, 0644);
+MODULE_PARM_DESC(rocket_npu_clk_hz,
+	"NPU compute clock target in Hz applied in runtime-resume (e.g. 600000000); 0 = stock 200 MHz");
+
 static void
 rocket_iommu_domain_destroy(struct kref *kref)
 {
@@ -246,6 +280,56 @@ static int rocket_device_runtime_resume(struct device *dev)
 		return err;
 	}
 
+	/*
+	 * The power domain for this core is now powered (the PM core resumed the
+	 * genpd before calling us) and the bulk clocks are enabled, so it is safe
+	 * to (re)program the shared SCMI NPU compute clock here. Setting it cold,
+	 * with the domain off (DT of_clk_set_defaults at probe, or an external
+	 * module), wedges the SCMI firmware -- so do it ONLY from here.
+	 *
+	 * Under rocket_clk_lock: the rate is shared, so this must not interleave
+	 * with a sibling core's park in rocket_device_runtime_suspend().
+	 */
+	mutex_lock(&rocket_clk_lock);
+
+	if (rocket_npu_clk_hz) {
+		struct clk *npu_clk = rdev->cores[core].npu_clk;
+
+		if (!npu_clk) {
+			dev_warn(dev, "rocket: no \"npu\" clock; cannot apply %lu Hz\n",
+				 rocket_npu_clk_hz);
+		} else {
+			int r = clk_set_rate(npu_clk, rocket_npu_clk_hz);
+
+			if (r) {
+				/*
+				 * Undo the bulk-clock enable and PROPAGATE the failure: a
+				 * degraded resume must not silently return 0 with the device
+				 * half-programmed. The PM core then leaves the domain
+				 * suspended rather than running at an unintended rate. The
+				 * refcount is NOT taken -- this core never held the rate.
+				 */
+				dev_warn(dev, "rocket: clk_set_rate(npu, %lu Hz) failed: %d (failing resume)\n",
+					 rocket_npu_clk_hz, r);
+				mutex_unlock(&rocket_clk_lock);
+				clk_bulk_disable_unprepare(ARRAY_SIZE(rdev->cores[core].clks),
+							   rdev->cores[core].clks);
+				return r;
+			}
+
+			dev_info(dev, "rocket: core %d NPU clk -> %lu Hz (reads back %lu)\n",
+				 core, rocket_npu_clk_hz, clk_get_rate(npu_clk));
+		}
+	}
+
+	/*
+	 * This core now holds the shared rate. Counted even when rocket_npu_clk_hz
+	 * is 0 (stock), so the count always tracks resumed cores and a runtime flip
+	 * of the param cannot strand it.
+	 */
+	rocket_clk_users++;
+	mutex_unlock(&rocket_clk_lock);
+
 	return 0;
 }
 
@@ -260,6 +344,33 @@ static int rocket_device_runtime_suspend(struct device *dev)
 	if (!rocket_job_is_idle(&rdev->cores[core]))
 		return -EBUSY;
 
+	/*
+	 * Park the compute clock back at the vendor power-down rate (200 MHz)
+	 * while the domain is still powered, so it never powers off (and back on)
+	 * at a raised rate -- mirroring the vendor's POWER_DOWN_FREQ handling.
+	 *
+	 * ONLY when this is the LAST core down. The rate is one shared SCMI clock;
+	 * parking it per-core cuts it out from under siblings that are still
+	 * running, and (worse) they never re-raise it, because an already-active
+	 * device gets no resume callback. See rocket_clk_users.
+	 *
+	 * The decrement sits after the rocket_job_is_idle() -EBUSY bail above: a
+	 * core that refuses to suspend still holds the rate.
+	 */
+	mutex_lock(&rocket_clk_lock);
+
+	if (rocket_clk_users)
+		rocket_clk_users--;
+
+	if (rocket_npu_clk_hz) {
+		struct clk *npu_clk = rdev->cores[core].npu_clk;
+
+		if (npu_clk && rocket_clk_users == 0)
+			clk_set_rate(npu_clk, ROCKET_NPU_POWER_DOWN_HZ);
+	}
+
+	mutex_unlock(&rocket_clk_lock);
+
 	clk_bulk_disable_unprepare(ARRAY_SIZE(rdev->cores[core].clks), rdev->cores[core].clks);
 
 	return 0;
-- 
2.43.0

